  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Implementation Steps**\n\nI\'m currently focused on how to safely integrate Deck.gl and MapLibre when they\'re loaded as window globals within the React application\'s `/src/App.tsx` file. I\'m exploring potential wrapper solutions for a cleaner implementation. The primary goal is to effectively use Deck.gl for rendering purposes within this context.\n\n\n**Exploring React Wrapper Solutions**\n\nI\'m now thinking about how to integrate Deck.gl as a custom React component using a ref-based approach. The plan involves utilizing a `useEffect` hook to initialize Deck.gl directly on a ref div or canvas, which provides complete control. This is looking like a solid path forward, providing the flexibility needed for the project.\n\n\n**Verifying Initialization Approach**\n\nI\'m now confirming the straightforward approach of initializing Deck.gl within a React component using `useRef` and `useEffect`, checking for the availability of `window.deck` and `window.maplibregl`. I can directly access Deck.gl exports like `DeckGL`, `ScatterplotLayer`, etc., from `(window as any).deck`, which is cleaner than other approaches. This method avoids bundling issues and ensures seamless integration, directly reflecting the user\'s JavaScript snippet.\n\n\n**Implementing Data & Filtering**\n\nI\'m now integrating `ITES_DATA` and `TRIPS_DATA` from `/src/data.ts` and setting up state for categories and selected sites. My focus is ensuring immediate updates to both the sidebar list and the Deck.gl layers based on category filtering. A historical-style search bar is next, aiming for the \"Zero Cyber\" aesthetic.\n\n\n**Designing Animation Implementation**\n\nNow, I\'m delving into the continuous animation of the `TripsLayer`. I\'ve realized that directly updating the Deck.gl instance within an animation frame loop or high-frequency interval inside a `useEffect` hook, rather than triggering React re-renders, is the key. The React component will maintain the `deckgl` instance via `useRef`, allowing for 60fps updates to the underlying layers. I\'m excited about the design, since it avoids unnecessary re-renders. I plan to center the map state on the selected site.\n\n\n**Refining Interaction Mechanics**\n\nI\'m now integrating continuous animation and interactive features for the visualization. The goal is to optimize both Deck.gl performance and React\'s declarative style. I have a `deckInstanceRef` mapping to the `DeckGL` instance. The core approach is a `renderLayers` method that regenerates the layers based on state changes (categories, site selection, animation ticks), calling `setProps` on the `deckInstanceRef.current` instance. I\'m focusing on user interactions, where `onViewStateChange` will capture map view updates and use refs to manage state efficiently. A site click calls `setProps` with transition properties.\n\n\n**Defining Category Symbol Atlas**\n\nI\'m now focusing on mapping the category details perfectly. I\'ve verified the HTML category mappings: `all`, `acqua`, `catacomba`, `rifugio`, and `ipogeo`. I\'ve confirmed the corresponding colors. The next step involves creating a visually appealing SVG atlas for these categories. My goal is historical and custom symbol representations.\n\n\n**Crafting Aesthetic Visuals**\n\nI\'m now designing the application\'s visual elements to achieve a professional and authentic feel. I\'ve defined four distinct icons: an aqueduct or water droplet for \'Acqua,\' a tomb or crypt for \'Catacomba,\' a shelter or guard\'s shield for \'Rifugio,\' and a chamber or vault for \'Ipogeo.\' These are designed to be historically-themed. My intention is to render these as inline SVG components in React, enabling dynamic coloring and precise positioning. I\'m focusing on the user\'s requested sidebar layout next.\n\n\n**Implementing Sidebar Panel**\n\nNow I\'m focusing on the implementation of the sidebar\'s detailed panel, `#ns-detail`. The goal is to show a description of the selected site with an animated transition. The panel, designed to expand gracefully at the bottom of the sidebar (`#ns-sidebar`), aligns perfectly with the provided CSS and HTML structure.\n\n\n**Designing Detail Panel Content**\n\nI\'m now implementing the sidebar\'s detail panel, leveraging flexbox to pin it to the bottom. I\'ll dynamically control the visibility and content. Initially, it\'ll display a placeholder message in Italian, \"Selezionare un sito per leggerne l\'architettura sotterranea e attivare la navigazione geospaziale.\" When a site is selected, the panel will display `.visible` with site-specific details. My focus is polished historical design.\n\n\n\n**Integrating Map and Deck**\n\nI\'m now integrating MapLibre and Deck.gl, considering potential issues with global variables in TypeScript, and a way to robustly declare these. I\'m exploring a declaration section within `/src/App.tsx`, specifically utilizing `declare global` to avoid TypeScript errors. I will ensure proper container design with HTML and CSS for `#map-wrapper`.\n\n\n**Simplifying Library Integration**\n\nI\'m now really excited! Deck.gl is built to integrate directly with MapLibre, as I am using the CDN build. I can pass the map container and style, letting Deck.gl create and manage the map, eliminating wrapper complications. I\'m focusing on those parameters now.\n\n\n**Defining Component Architecture**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a modular React architecture. I\'ve broken the application into key components for clarity: `/src/types.ts` for data interfaces, `/src/data.ts` for the database, and `/src/components` for the visual elements. This enables better maintainability and will be key. I\'ll focus on sidebar components and the map view container now.\n\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `/src/components/SvgAtlas.tsx` to store and export our four classic archeological symbols: **Acqua**, **Catacomba**, **Rifugio**, and **Ipogeo**. They are rendered in gold with historical lines and geometry, matching the \"Zero Cyber\" requirement. Let\'s create the file."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 20
      nanos: 372547071
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
