    thinking: "**Prioritizing Project Initiation**\n\nOkay, I\'ve decided to prioritize project initiation. Initially, I considered building either a `Sidebar.tsx` file or the interactive map components immediately. However, I have paused to research map construction in React applications first. The user\'s request prioritizes a Motore Deck.gl with smooth zoom/pan controls, icon management, and viewstate in `app.js`.\n\n\n**Analyzing Layer Implementation**\n\nI\'m now focusing on how the user implemented the layers in their original code. Specifically, I\'m examining the `ScatterplotLayer` for the archeological symbols, as it offers the base for the requested `IconLayer`. I\'m going to determine what\'s best to refactor for the target `Motore Deck.gl` and how to optimize for the `smooth zoom/pan controls, icon management, and viewstate in app.js` requirement.\n\n\n**Evaluating Layer Choice**\n\nI\'m now weighing the best approach for the archeological symbols. Initially, I noticed the user\'s comment about a `ScatterplotLayer` for high visibility and click resolution. The target is an `IconLayer`, but I\'m considering customization within a `ScatterplotLayer`. I\'m comparing the `IconLayer`\'s SVG support with the potential of a custom, high-fidelity SVG marker. The user has simplified the process significantly. It looks like it is very easy to build client-side layers. I can build both options!\n\n\n**Implementing SVG Icons**\n\nOkay, I\'ve confirmed that inline SVG data URIs work beautifully within Deck.gl\'s `IconLayer`. I can define icons directly using data URIs in the `getIcon` prop. I\'m exploring the colors for masking and considering a dual-layer strategy: a glowing outer `ScatterplotLayer` for depth/categories combined with the original\'s high-fidelity `ScatterplotLayer` and `TextLayer` labels, or custom SVG markers within an `IconLayer`. If dependency issues arise with the `IconLayer`, I can utilize both high-contrast and elegant layers.\n\n\n**Constructing Map Engine**\n\nI\'m now writing the Deck.gl map container in React. I\'ve realized, because `deck` and `maplibregl` are loaded globally, a `useEffect` hook in the React component can instantiate them directly. I need the component to handle `selectedSite`, `categoryFilter`, `searchQuery`, and an `onSelectSite` callback for site clicks. I\'ll make sure the markers look top-tier by leveraging full compatibility.\n\n\n**Integrating Animation Loop**\n\nI\'m now investigating animation with a `TripsLayer`. I\'ll implement a `requestAnimationFrame` loop within my `useEffect` hook to update a high-performance state counter, avoiding unnecessary React re-renders. The loop will only modify layer properties. I aim to ensure a smooth, performant animation within the Deck.gl map, to update the trips data as intended.\n\n\n**Refining Tooltip Logic**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the layer\'s tooltip details. I\'ve integrated HTML with inline styling for the tooltips, improving their visual appeal, including a border, font styling, and color coding. The goal is an enhanced user experience with the `Motore Deck.gl` map. I\'m focusing on the rendering performance.\n\n\n**Implementing Fly-To Logic**\n\nI\'m now implementing the \"fly to\" functionality for selected sites within the Deck.gl map. A secondary `useEffect` hook will listen for changes in `selectedSite`, and when it changes, the map will be updated using a transition interpolator for smooth animation. The zoom, longitude, latitude, and pitch will be updated. The goal is a highly intuitive user experience for site navigation.\n\n\n\n**Confirming Layer Updates**\n\nI\'ve just confirmed the synchronization of `viewStateRef.current` with changes in `selectedSite`. The use of `setProps` now delivers a smooth, buttery 60fps fly-to animation. I\'m also ensuring immediate rendering of filtered sites via the `useEffect` hook, responding to `categoryFilter` and `searchQuery` changes.\n\n\n**Refining Layer Implementation**\n\nI\'m now integrating the `TripsLayer` for water channel visualization alongside the site markers. The data filtering is working. I\'m leveraging `ScatterplotLayer` for a glowing effect on the selected site, which I will then refactor. The filter also ensures immediate rendering of updates. I\'ve chosen to use `filtered.filter` for efficient data selection. The glowing sites are beautiful.\n\n\n**Optimizing Marker Aesthetics**\n\nI\'m now refining the visual styling of the site markers and labels, specifically the `ScatterplotLayer` for markers. I\'m focusing on the border, and ensuring that the selected sites display a clear, bright white border. The labels and markers are well integrated with each other. I\'m leveraging `TextLayer` to refine the labels next to the markers, and trimming long subnames. I\'m ensuring both a high level of performance and visual clarity.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now create `/src/components/UndergroundMap.tsx` to handle our Deck.gl mapping canvas. This component integrates with the globally loaded MapLibre GL instance, loads the \"Dark Matter\" historical slate base maps, animates water channels, manages camera state transitions, and notifies our React core when users select individual objects directly on the map. Let\'s write the file."
