    thinking: "**Evaluating Initial Impressions**\n\nOkay, I\'m finding this initial view quite aesthetically pleasing. My immediate next step is to examine `/src/components/UndergroundMap.tsx`. I intend to focus on ensuring correct state closure with useRefs, aligning the map projection with MapLibre, and exploring smaller, more thematic icons for the visualization. Let\'s dig in and see what\'s there!\n\n\n**Synchronizing Component States**\n\nI\'ve just implemented state synchronization with refs for `categoryFilter`, `searchQuery`, and `selectedSite`. This involved creating ref instances and ensuring their values are updated on every render. Now, the `updateLayers()` function pulls data from these refs, ensuring that the most current filter and selection data is applied to the map. This looks to prevent issues of outdated state!\n\n\n**Refining Layer Filtering Logic**\n\nI\'ve just refined the layer filtering logic, ensuring seamless interaction. The current implementation now accurately filters based on active category and search queries. This looks really clean and robust now, instantly resolving any closure issues. I have made the filter logic very concise to prevent future errors. I have also added `maplibregl` to deckGL, to prevent projection shifts!\n\n\n**Considering Map Style Harmony**\n\nI\'m now contemplating the map style and its visual harmony with the user\'s color scheme. The initial dark style conflicts. I\'ve found that CartoDB\'s \"positron\" style, with its light gray tones, may pair exceptionally well with the sand/parchment background and scholarly aesthetic. I\'m torn on either \"positron\" or \"dark-matter\" depending on the user\'s preference!\n\n\n**Selecting Aesthetic Map Style**\n\nI\'ve decided that a light street map is best for visual harmony, and I am leaning towards the CartoDB \"positron\" style. It appears to be stunning with the EB Garamond palette, with white and light streets. I\'ve now considered our markers, and their vibrant colors should stand out like an authentic antique surveyor\'s map! Now, I am exploring whether we should scale the icons to smaller sizes, maybe thematically!\n\n\n**Adjusting Thematic Visuals**\n\nI\'ve made the Scatterplot layer smaller to enhance precision and added EB Garamond for the text labels, which looks great! I\'m now working to match the legend panel with the brand style, applying the exact colors, font, and border. I\'m also reviewing the selected aura glow to ensure visual harmony with these new changes.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now edit `/src/components/UndergroundMap.tsx` to:\n1. **Synchronize Coordinates and Prevent Drift**: Add `maplibregl: (window as any).maplibregl` to bind DeckGL\'s camera projection directly with the underlying map tiles, eliminating coordinate shifting under zoom and drag.\n2. **Resolve Category Click & Filtering Block**: Use React `useRef` tokens (`categoryFilterRef`, `searchQueryRef`, `selectedSiteRef`) to pass state references into the active canvas frame render loop, completely bypassing stale JavaScript closure blocks.\n3. **Apply the EB Garamond & Sand-Crimson Style Card**: Transition the map container elements, the floating legend, vector tooltips, and map markers to the elegant, bright sand-cream, terracotta, and deep-wine visual theme.\n4. **Thematic Miniaturized Icons**: Reduce map marker radii and adjust labels, rendering exquisite pinpoint survey indicators."
