    thinking: "**Analyzing App.tsx**\n\nOkay, I\'ve started examining `App.tsx`! My focus is the category filter labels, specifically how to shorten them for a cleaner layout with five columns. Avoiding ugly line breaks and overflowing margins is key; I\'m considering \"TUTTO\", \"ACQUA\", \"CATA\", \"RIFUGI\", and \"IPOGEI\" as potential shorter labels for each category to solve this issue.\n\n\n**Refining Category Titles**\n\nI\'m now diving into the `getCategoryTitle` function in `App.tsx` (line 52). My thinking has evolved; I\'m no longer just shortening existing names. I\'ve considered how to replace them entirely! Instead of the initial approach, I\'m aiming for concise, impactful labels like \"ACQUA\", \"CRIPTE\", \"RIFUGI\", \"IPOGEI\", and \"TUTTO\". \"CRIPTE\" is particularly elegant. I will be checking how they fit in the button layout (line 91).\n\n\n**Updating Theme Colors**\n\nI\'ve shifted focus to theme color updates within `App.tsx`. Specifically, I\'m integrating the new gold color, now mapped to `#92400E`, replacing previous mentions of `gold`. I am also analyzing the background colors of the elements; I think that a parchment color (`#FFEDDD`) would work best for the body and sidebar background to fit the light theme, instead of the darker tones.\n\n\n**Refining Sidebar Styling**\n\nI\'m now fully immersed in styling the sidebar! My latest iteration leans into a light cream background (`#FFEDDD`) for the sidebar wrapper and white (`#FFFFFF`) for the card lists, creating a clean contrast. Text will be deep crimson (`#3A0000`) for a touch of elegance. I am also working on the specific details to the sidebar elements, such as the font, size, and layout, and they are now ready. The sidebar elements follow the light theme guidelines.\n\n\n**Styling Search & Input**\n\nI am now focusing on the search functionality within the app, specifically the styling of the search input and associated elements. I\'ve been fine-tuning the input\'s appearance, its placeholder text, and the search icon\'s positioning and visual styling. I am also considering the responsiveness and overall user experience to ensure smooth interaction. I have also added hover effects.\n\n\n**Optimizing Page Layout**\n\nI\'m now integrating new components into the layout. Specifically, I have worked on adding the site\'s statistic bar, with `Compass`, `TrendingDown`, and the app version. I\'ve also incorporated the scrolling site list section with a light off-white background and light gold shadows. I\'m focusing on ensuring these additions contribute to a clean and efficient layout, maintaining a user-friendly design.\n\n\n**Adjusting Footer Details**\n\nI\'m now integrating style changes to the detailed panel footer, focusing on the main map area. The footer\'s styling uses `#F5EDD8` as the background color and `#0A0806` text color. I\'m focusing on these elements to make the design match the new image color palette. I\'m refining the footer height and layout, with a custom height, background and text color, and border top. I\'ve updated the styles for the left container and the title detail, to align with a stronger theme.\n\n\n**Refining Utility Button**\n\nI\'ve just added the \"Visualizza Rilievo 3D\" utility button. I\'m focusing on its visual cues: a deep crimson border and a hover state that flips the colors to a parchment text on a crimson background. The text is in a small, uppercase, bold font. The interactive button will appear in the page when a site is selected. I\'m prioritizing clarity in its design to highlight its function.\n\n\n\n**Updating Detail Section**\n\nI\'m now styling the detailed site description section. I\'m focusing on the `className` attributes, especially the `bg-gradient-to-r` and font sizes. The goal is to make the dossier header more readable with a smaller text size, a subtle opacity, and the right colors. The description text now utilizes a slightly larger font size and optimized line spacing.\n\n\n"
