      title: "github.com"
    }
    web_documents {
      url: "https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE35Mill-fm-dmXCjuvWVyp_oWx1js_P3cf8wAlwu_M0B_QRu2MkTw3YK6a6Pwwyif-GHViKBuYS9BkVyPpkfYoYmmlFJvEXcHLYmJcQdJBzY0J2pT-ZtZ5nmH5ZqwLXvoKsNkbJ0nk4u8BBFVeEhpapEWy"
      title: "deck.gl"
    }
    summary: "`MapboxOverlay` from `deck.gl` can be effectively used with `maplibre-gl` to integrate powerful WebGL-powered data visualizations into your maps. This integration is supported in both JavaScript and TypeScript, with various examples and documentation available.\n\n### Integration Modes\n\nWhen combining `deck.gl` with `maplibre-gl` using `MapboxOverlay`, there are primarily three integration modes to consider[1]:\n\n*   **Interleaved**: This mode renders `deck.gl` layers directly into the WebGL2 context created by MapLibre. It is ideal for mixing `deck.gl` layers with MapLibre layers, allowing for correct 3D occlusion and positioning (e.g., `deck.gl` surfaces appearing below text labels). This requires `maplibre-gl@>3` and `interleaved: true` in the `MapboxOverlay` configuration.[1]\n*   **Overlaid**: In this mode, `deck.gl` renders in a separate canvas positioned within MapLibre\'s controls container. This is suitable if your use case doesn\'t require interleaving but you still want to utilize MapLibre GL JS controls (like `NavigationControl` or `Popup`) or plugins. This is achieved by setting `interleaved: false` (the default) in `MapboxOverlay`.[1]\n*   **Reverse-Controlled**: This mode renders `deck.gl` above the MapLibre container, taking over pointer input handling and managing the map\'s size and camera. This is useful for custom input handling or when using Deck.gl\'s multi-view features, but it means you cannot use `maplibre-gl` controls or plugins.[1]\n\n### JavaScript Examples\n\nFor pure JavaScript implementations, `MapboxOverlay` is added as a control to the MapLibre map.\n\n*   **Basic Overlaid/Interleaved Example**: The `deck.gl` documentation provides a \"pure JS get-started example\" that demonstrates how to use `MapboxOverlay` to render `deck.gl` layers, allowing you to switch between interleaved and overlaid rendering[1].\n*   **Interleaving with 3D Buildings**: An example showcases interleaving `deck.gl` layers (like `ScatterplotLayer` and `ArcLayer`) with MapLibre\'s 3D buildings, demonstrating how to control layer order using `beforeId`.[2]\n*   **Toggling Deck.gl Layers**: A practical example illustrates how to add `MapboxOverlay` as a control and dynamically toggle the visibility of `deck.gl` layers on a MapLibre map.[3][4]\n\n### TypeScript Examples\n\nFor TypeScript projects, you can leverage `MapboxOverlay` similarly, often within a React context using `react-map-gl`, a React wrapper for `maplibre-gl`.\n\n*   **Deck.gl with TerrainLayer**: A StackBlitz example demonstrates using `MapboxOverlay` with a `TerrainLayer` from `deck.gl` within a MapLibre GL JS map, written in TypeScript.[5]\n*   **React Integration**: If you\'re using React, `react-map-gl` is the recommended companion. `MapboxOverlay` can be used with `react-map-gl`\'s `useControl` hook for interleaved or overlaid options.[1]\n*   **Comprehensive TypeScript Examples**: The `opengeos/maplibre-gl-typescript-examples` GitHub repository offers a wide array of MapLibre GL JS features converted to TypeScript, including examples that integrate with `deck.gl`.[6]\n*   **MapboxOverlay API Reference**: The `MapboxOverlay` documentation itself includes TypeScript examples for its usage.[7]\n\n### Key Considerations\n\n*   `MapboxOverlay` functions as an implementation of Mapbox GL JS\'s `IControl` API, allowing `deck.gl` layers to synchronize with the base map.[7]\n*   You can control the rendering order of `deck.gl` layers within the Mapbox/MapLibre stack by using the `beforeId` prop on individual `deck.gl` layers.[7]\n*   For advanced scenarios involving multiple views, `MapboxOverlay` supports limited multi-view capabilities, with a dedicated `MapView` with the ID \"mapbox\" for synchronization.[7]\n\nSources:\n[1] [deck.gl](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEGaeAL1zBnhf-Vb-PE87PFoxPxeVuCuSll0NJidmmCaUE9JNJIN5P6UBTL8Vo1jSkU53j3fCkAuXsJ89aPa7wWc0krTJiPbNdWYyZXheylmlYkfhLkTUJ1Awg0l5FH-8zgbW6BqTPthOsI-fGzDyvrWuOpWb_7fY89AaUZPA==)\n[2] [deck.gl](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQHQm3gUAbU7pDSstmxOsK9aKN6WC23yHiGbq78w__FlL2u4kFU0ZApFw_g-0PyFv7doKQM9FW0HpVrBm_s74FNQdrvNa4KMJArl_oiF8ZnMtFL4F5vDtaCHneioL4Yc1LCaMp0=)\n[3] [maplibre.org](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQFWPMkL_a6Bzxjy7MPYLICl1iR6YGpzzQ37ImX5TXCTadfcDxa8s7PixhAr-tlB9zY_JEJWqamAKDBse4bQ-CrDuoqR2xIEw7v3OE2YJl-3I8g7ZX44oFp6PvdvZGnal1etmnjL221FmNekyiTg2FucrsW6sRk3IZeFDm6ViNRC07U=)\n[4] [clockworkmicro.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEWMONxO8zYVjNJxY36Ry_Ya2KiIti1uZieQdsSpKfZGdLT748X1L5yqZGUMw8z1-qjnvapPHpMLEb6s5dEgKKGPehanLgoV0ztItGNILVro6_FV0yE2hhalm-VPR8oRyRCFeEBtVxfenmsjn22kpWmaci7s_4icPsdSxVpF1HcocI-j35Jxw==)\n[5] [stackblitz.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQEqnwdXbbgaLKgDlL4iQ2_AkYdHR-YeuePVtXbAH42CSXJX-rukeb0f52tHNHFBrGElT27m8Lm5b5WZQbarRLZIXFV9yUFCKagEaU0oUUmG2VreJpeCuv2kgTxZOPkfqFkxPpfgd8LE1Q==)\n[6] [github.com](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQH2HrBX_Hx8gyS1KdyogplN6Rc3tKXSODPVZw4iXKtIGOR7WYHF108CADEpfdJMpijlw-NoN_J9BqSuZQGyzapRqgAJrem6hY3BaoA0-XvJeFU98YHkvcw24wYLR9VxlkyXWrjEOIGn6uPWNp0OXJ-c8MriQiHu)\n[7] [deck.gl](https://vertexaisearch.cloud.google.com/grounding-api-redirect/AUZIYQE35Mill-fm-dmXCjuvWVyp_oWx1js_P3cf8wAlwu_M0B_QRu2MkTw3YK6a6Pwwyif-GHViKBuYS9BkVyPpkfYoYmmlFJvEXcHLYmJcQdJBzY0J2pT-ZtZ5nmH5ZqwLXvoKsNkbJ0nk4u8BBFVeEhpapEWy)"
