  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Considering Integration**\n\nThe installation of `@deck.gl/mapbox` was flawless; that was a great relief! Now, I\'m delving into its compatibility with `maplibre-gl` Map. I\'m focusing on how viewState updates and mouse click actions are handled. Specifically, how the layer reacts when a site is clicked on the map.\n\n\n**Verifying Pickability**\n\nI\'m thrilled; pickability events, including clicks, are functioning perfectly with `MapboxOverlay`! I\'ve confirmed `ScatterplotLayer` markers and tooltips respond as expected. Next, I\'m integrating a `maplibre-gl` style map as the base, overlaid by DeckGL graphics via `MapboxOverlay`. My focus now is on cleanly structuring the React component and managing references to both the map and overlay instances using `useRef`. I\'m using `.flyTo` directly on the `maplibre-gl` map instance for cinematic focusing, which is more native and integrates beautifully. I\'m taking a close look at how the layers will be computed within the `updateLayers` function.\n\n\n**Refining Layer Computation**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the `getLayers` function. The goal is to build a master renderer that efficiently handles filtering and dynamic updates. I\'m focusing on the interplay of filters, search queries, and selected sites. The TripsLayer is a high priority, to ensure the path data is rendered smoothly and with good performance. I am also currently working on the visual style to match the existing map style.\n\n\n**Implementing Visual Enhancements**\n\nI\'ve been working on a series of visual enhancements to highlight site selections. I\'m focusing on three primary layer types. The first is a dynamic TripsLayer, which I\'ve got running. Then, I\'m working on a \"selected aura\" glow effect, visualized with a ScatterplotLayer, which is conditionally rendered based on active site selections. And finally, I\'m integrating miniaturized thematic markers using a ScatterplotLayer to give visual cues based on category.\n\n\n**Adding Visual Cues**\n\nI\'ve crafted a ScatterplotLayer to indicate site categories, using colors for \"rifugio\" and \"ipogei\". It features dynamic radii and borders for active selections, with click events. A TextLayer now displays site names elegantly.\n\n\n**Integrating Tooltips**\n\nI\'ve realized I can integrate the tooltips seamlessly by passing a `getTooltip` function directly to the `MapboxOverlay`\'s configuration. This approach simplifies the tooltip implementation because it allows for easy control of the display for our active and off-active selected sites. I can now manage the display of the data directly within the `MapboxOverlay` component.\n\n\n**Styling Tooltips Correctly**\n\nI\'m now focusing on tooltip styling, specifically ensuring the `.deck-tooltip` class is correctly applied and styled. I need to make sure the tooltip displays correctly. I\'m verifying the `maplibre-gl.css` import to confirm its influence on the map\'s dimensions and ensuring the map covers 100% of the container. I\'m also ensuring the map-wrapper container is correctly styled.\n\n\n**Confirming Layout**\n\nI\'m making sure the map container is correctly styled. The `w-full h-full` Tailwind classes on the `ref={mapContainerRef}` element are a perfect solution. I\'m also confirming that the parent container\'s configuration meets `maplibregl` requirements. I\'m moving toward writing the `useEffect` hook to initialize the `map` and `overlay`.\n\n\n**Finalizing Tooltip Integration**\n\nI\'ve integrated a custom tooltip directly into the MapboxOverlay using a `getTooltip` function to render the HTML content, complete with styled elements and dynamic data. The tooltip displays name, depth, and category, and is styled elegantly with custom CSS and font details. I\'m leveraging Tailwind classes for responsive design, ensuring a clean and informative display. I\'m using `getTooltip` to create an optimal user experience.\n\n\n**Observing Trigger Events**\n\nI\'m now integrating an animation frame render loop within the useEffect hook for dynamic updates to TripsLayers. I\'m also ensuring the viewState is continuously updated when the map moves, synchronizing the camera with any external controls. I\'m focusing on ensuring the useEffect cleanup function correctly removes the overlay and the map to avoid memory leaks and ensure the application runs smoothly.\n\n\n**Refining Animation Integration**\n\nI\'m thrilled with the simplicity of the `useEffect` hooks for site updates and cinematic focus. The `setProps` in the overlay now immediately triggers a re-render. I\'ve eliminated animation drift and complexity by using `maplibre-gl`\'s native camera controls. The site changes are fast and the cinematic integration is smooth.\n\n\n**Examining Dependencies**\n\nI\'m now carefully examining dependencies, specifically how to replace the existing file content with a fresh implementation. I\'m focusing on ensuring all imports are correct. I\'m also confirming I can use a global style without requiring API keys. This will simplify deployment.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will now edit `/src/components/UndergroundMap.tsx` to fully implement the `MapboxOverlay` pattern with native `maplibre-gl` camera flights. This will bring back the gorgeous positron antique style map safely, align coordinates perfectly with no offset/drift, and render our archaeological markers and flows correctly in full compatibility with React 19 and ESM module bundling. Let me overwrite the file with the clean implementation."
